{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476452","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476452"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:47:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:47:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13742"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13742","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13742"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.35,0.04,0.28,0.31,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6361"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112883"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6361","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6361"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13742"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94920"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"2228"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11813"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13851"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15480"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16000"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19305"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35604"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40275"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45282"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45283"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45284"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45285"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46424"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112883","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112883"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a five-day history of fever, cough and lethargy. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. His immunisations are up to date. He is able to eat and drink small amounts. On examination, he appears unwell with a pulse rate of 130/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 32/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 39.1\u00b0C. Chest auscultation reveals bronchial breath sounds and crackles in the right lower zone. A chest X-ray shows dense consolidation in the right lower lobe, consistent with lobar pneumonia.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral amoxicillin","Oral azithromycin","Intravenous benzylpenicillin","Intravenous ceftriaxone","Oral prednisolone"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child presents with moderate community-acquired pneumonia, but is able to tolerate oral intake. In this scenario, \u003Cstrong\u003Eoral amoxicillin\u003C/strong\u003E is the first-line antibiotic according to Australian guidelines, including the Therapeutic Guidelines. Amoxicillin provides excellent coverage against \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pneumoniae\u003C/em\u003E, the most common bacterial cause of pneumonia in children. Oral therapy is appropriate for children who are able to eat and drink, even if hospitalised, as it is effective and avoids the risks and discomfort of intravenous administration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous benzylpenicillin\u003C/strong\u003E is an appropriate alternative if the child is unable to tolerate oral medications due to vomiting, severe illness, or complications such as empyema. However, in this case, the child is able to take oral medications, so intravenous therapy is not required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous ceftriaxone\u003C/strong\u003E is reserved for children who cannot tolerate oral therapy and have a history of penicillin allergy, or in settings where there is a high prevalence of penicillin-resistant \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pneumoniae\u003C/em\u003E. It is not first-line in children who can take oral amoxicillin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral azithromycin\u003C/strong\u003E is considered if there is suspicion of atypical pathogens (such as \u003Cem\u003EMycoplasma pneumoniae\u003C/em\u003E) or in children with a history of penicillin allergy. It is not first-line for typical community-acquired pneumonia in this age group.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral prednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E does not have a role in the management of uncomplicated bacterial pneumonia in children. Corticosteroids are not routinely recommended unless there is another indication, such as underlying asthma or severe airway inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to antibiotics, supportive care with supplemental oxygen to maintain SpO2 above 92%, hydration, and analgesia/antipyretics is essential. The choice of antibiotic should always consider local resistance patterns, individual patient factors, and be guided by local hospital guidelines.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Oral amoxicillin is the first-line antibiotic for community-acquired pneumonia in children who can tolerate oral intake, even if hospitalised.","Intravenous antibiotics are reserved for children who are unable to tolerate oral therapy or have severe disease with complications.","Supportive care with supplemental oxygen, hydration and analgesia are important adjuncts to antibiotic therapy in pneumonia management."],"references":["Barson WJ. Pneumonia in children: Inpatient treatment. In: UpToDate [online]. 2024. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/pneumonia-in-children-inpatient-treatment","Davies HD. Community-acquired pneumonia in children. Paediatr Child Health. 2003 Dec;8(10):616-9. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2795279/","Royal Children\u0027s Hospital, Melbourne. Clinical practice guideline: Community acquired pneumonia [Internet]. Last updated October\u00a02023 [cited\u00a02025\u00a0Aug\u00a06]. Available from: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Community_acquired_pneumonia/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94920"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13742"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94920","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94920"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-07T14:39:15+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-07T14:40:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6361"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112883"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags